<HEADLINE>
FT  21 OCT 92 / Ministers relent on town hall tendering
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MINISTERS are preparing to soften their approach to extending compulsory
competitive tendering to local authority white-collar services because of
the difficulty in devising a sensible way of taking account of the quality
of work.
The move will mark an abandonment of the scheme set out in a government
consultation paper last year, which proposed a 'quality threshold' for
tendering in areas such as architectural and engineering services.
That suggestion came in for widespread criticism, not least from the
relevant professional organisations.
Officials now argue that while these services should still be subject to
compulsory tendering, the government should not attempt to impose a
'straitjacket' on how local authorities carry out the process.
'We are moving to a less dirigiste policy,' one Whitehall insider said
yesterday.
The original proposal was a 'double envelope' system, under which unpriced
tenders were initially considered against a pre-set quality threshold,
followed by a further evaluation, so the lowest-priced tender was
automatically accepted from those meeting or exceeding the threshold.
Ministers are keen that the step back from specifying how quality should be
addressed should not be seen as diluting their commitment to extending
competitive tendering.
They are determined that April 1994 will remain the date after which any new
work will be carried out by in-house staff only if it has been won in
competition.
In private, however, officials admit that, unless the government insists on
a detailed procedure, the scope for a council which does not want to
contract out professional services to continue to award work to in-house
tenders is so great that much of the policy's impact will be lost.
The Department of the Environment has already experienced similar problems
with the introduction of compulsory tendering to blue-collar services, where
standards are easier to define.
Mr Michael Howard, the environment secretary, will announce the revised
approach early next month, when MPs have their first chance to debate the
bill dealing with housing reforms and setting up the urban regeneration
agency.
The legislation includes the extension of tendering to local councils'
housing management, which will not be affected by this shift of emphasis.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
