FT  21 OCT 92 / Chrysler plans sales drive
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN GRIFFITHS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
ALL future Chrysler vehicles will be engineered for right-hand-drive as well
as left-hand-drive markets, the company said yesterday as it outlined plans
for a big UK sales campaign next year.
Its new UK importer, a subsidiary of the Inchcape-owned TKM vehicle
distribution group, expects to sell 2,000 Chrysler Jeep and other models in
the UK next year.
It plans to raise that to at least 17,000 a year by the end of the decade,
Mr Richard Mackay, managing director of Chrysler Jeep Imports UK, of Dover,
said at the motor show. The first models are to go on sale in January
through a network of 80 dealers.
One will be a variant of the Cherokee four-wheel-drive leisure vehicle,
built in Toledo, Ohio. That, Chrysler said yesterday, is the first
right-hand-drive production vehicle to be built in North America by a
US-owned volume carmaker for export to the UK.
The other will be a right-hand-drive model of the smaller Wrangler, the
latest version of the classic Jeep. Right-hand-drive models versions of
those were first developed through Chrysler's joint venture in China.
Mr Bernard Robertson, vice-president of jeep/truck engineering and
operations, said right-hand-drive models would give the company potential
access to 55 countries that drive on the left, accounting for 23 per cent of
world vehicle sales.
Chrysler's re-entry to the UK market, reversing its withdrawal in the 1970s,
is part of a much wider drive to establish a sales and production presence
in Europe. It sold 44,183 vehicles throughout Europe last year through a
sales and service network that now totals 1,500 outlets.
