<HEADLINE>
FT  21 OCT 92 / Patten moves to standardise GCSEs
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD EVANS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A MANDATORY code of practice covering all aspects of the GCSE examination is
to be introduced by Mr John Patten, education secretary, to ensure that even
standards are maintained throughout the country.
The move, which endorsed the recommendations of the government's advisers on
exams, follows a highly critical report by schools inspectors last month
warning that standards might be slipping. The proposal is the clearest
indication so far that Mr Patten is determined to raise academic standards.
The code of practice, to be drafted by the end of the year and introduced
before next summer's exams for 16-year-olds, is aimed at combating alleged
differences in the way some GCSE papers are set and marked by the five
examining boards in England and Wales.
Advice from the Schools Examination and Assessment Council, published
yesterday, supported the critical views expressed by inspectors last month.
The council concluded it was necessary to 'increase the transparency of the
examination process' to maintain public confidence in the GCSE.
The Education Department said that meant results should be 'more clearly
defined and more easily understood'.
The new code demands standardised marking and will also cover the setting of
questions, coursework assessment, grading of standards and boundaries, and
assessment of spelling, punctuation and grammar.
Mr Patten will be able to withdraw his approval from any examining board
that infringes the code. Boards are expected to toe the line as they are
businesses and need the support of schools and candidates' fees to survive.
Mr Patten said his purpose was to have an exam that pupils, teachers,
parents and employers could trust.
Lord Griffiths of Fforest-fach, council chairman, said in his report that
because the GCSE was introduced to provide greater motivation for students,
he would have expected an improvement in examination results.
He added: 'We are nevertheless concerned that the sharp increase in the
number of school leavers with five or more GCSE A to C grades in the last
two years raises questions about standards, which we are investigating.'
Mr Patten said he wanted more time to reflect on the council's call for a
wider review of the structure, funding and accountability of examining
groups. Lord Griffiths proposed the appointment by the council of external
GCSE marking and grading assessors, similar to the system of external
examiners used by universities.
The minister also welcomed the council's conclusion that other reforms being
prepared for 1994 - including limits on coursework, different papers to
stretch more able pupils, and marks for spelling, punctuation and grammar -
would strengthen the exam.
The Associated Examining Board, which had more than 800,000 GCSE entries
this summer, said the code of practice offered 'nothing new' and would
change little.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
