<HEADLINE>
FT  21 OCT 92 / NAO queries Pounds 40m Tec funds
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LISA WOOD, Labour Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE National Audit Office has questioned the accounts of the Department of
Employment for the third consecutive year and found that more than Pounds
21m of payments to Training and Enterprise Councils and the Employment
Service were incorrectly made. There is disagreement over a further Pounds
19m.
The payments in 1991-92 were among those made to employer-led Tecs and the
government's Employment Service. In the previous year, incorrect payments
totalled Pounds 53m.
Tecs are responsible for payments to about 4,000 providers of training for
young people and unemployed adults on the two main national training
programmes, Youth Training and Employment Training. The Employment Service
pays allowances to unemployed adults on ET. The total cost of the two
programmes was Pounds 1.5bn in 1991-92.
Among the lapses of financial control identified by the government's
spending watchdog were: paying youth trainees after their training had
ceased; claiming payments for vocational qualifications not gained in the
appropriate year; and allowing claims that were not adequately
substantiated.
Inadequate documentary evidence to support claims was a chief complaint by
the NAO. Tecs themselves complain about the complexity of audit trails
imposed upon them.
The report says: 'This arose from confusion regarding the evidence required
for qualifications and the problems relating to satisfactory and timely
documentation.'
In addition, there were claims that Tecs thought they had made legitimately
but which appeared to the Internal Audit to be ineligible. One Tec claimed
Pounds 153,000 for vocational qualifications gained by trainees between 1984
and 1989 - before the advent of the Tec.
The department, commenting on the report, said it was implementing a plan
for 100 per cent financial control by the end of March 1993.
Report by the Comptroller and Auditor General. NAO, Buckingham Palace Road,
London SW1W 9SP.
</TEXT>
