<HEADLINE>
FT  21 OCT 92 / Mitsubishi acts on import quota
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KEVIN DONE, Motor Industry Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MITSUBISHI, the Japanese carmaker, is to begin exporting cars to Europe from
Australia for the first time, allowing it to circumvent quota limits on
direct vehicle imports from Japan.
Like Honda and Toyota, it is already exporting cars from its US assembly
plant to Europe. The company yesterday displayed its Australian-built Sigma
estate car at the British motor show in Birmingham; a competitor for
vehicles such as the Ford Granada/Scorpio and Opel Omega/Vauxhall Carlton
estate cars.
The Japanese carmaker hopes to export 5,000 vehicles from Australia to
Europe next year, of which about 10 per cent will come to the UK.
Typical of the increasingly complex supply pattern in the world motor
industry, the Sigma estate car was developed by Mitsubishi Motors Australia
in Adelaide, which will become the sole production plant worldwide. The same
vehicle will also be exported by Mitsubishi from Australia to the US with
shipment of 6,000 vehicles planned next year.
The estate car is sold as the Mitsubishi Magna/Verada in Australia. The
export programme to Europe and the US will allow Mitsubishi Motors Australia
to increase output from 29,074 vehicles in 1991 to 38,700 this year and
52,000 in 1993, buoyed by a modest recovery in the Australian domestic
market.
Mitsubishi holds about 12.4 per cent of the total Australian vehicle market,
behind Toyota (20.6 per cent), Ford (19.7 per cent) and General Motors
(Holden) with 17.3 per cent. The company wants to increase the single-shift
capacity at its Adelaide plant from 57,000 to 74,000 by the mid 1990s. The
company claims to have a local Australian content of about 85 per cent for
its vehicles.
Mr Reijiro Kuromizu, a managing director of Mitsubishi Motors, said: 'We
have the problem of the quota system in the European Community (for Japanese
exports), so if we can source products from Australia or the US, that helps
our operations in Europe a great deal. That is the reason we started
shipping products from Australia and the US. You must have sufficient local
content in each location and we have complied with that.'
He said that Mitsubishi would export about 10,000 cars from the US to Europe
this year, chiefly to Germany, Italy, Sweden, Switzerland and Austria. The
company was also studying the shipment of light commercial vehicles to
Europe from Thailand.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 10
</PAGE>
