<HEADLINE>
FT  21 OCT 92 / Kinnock passed over for EC post
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IVO DAWNAY and LIONEL BARBER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   LONDON, BRUSSELS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE tortuous on-off saga of Mr Neil Kinnock's possible appointment as a
Brussels commissioner finally ended last night when it was confirmed that Mr
Bruce Millan will remain in his post for a further two years.
The decision immediately provoked behind-the-scenes charges of bad faith
against Mr John Major from senior Labour officials and fervent
counter-denials from Downing Street that the prime minister had given any
undertakings to the former opposition leader.
Last July, Mr Major held a series of talks with Mr John Smith, Mr Kinnock's
successor, over Labour's nominee for the post of second British
commissioner.
While officials emphasised that the final decision remained firmly in the
prime minister's hands, there were widespread reports that, fresh from his
April election triumph, Mr Major was in magnanimous mood and ready to
approve the posting.
Commentators also pointed out that Mr Smith might have his own reasons for
pressing the appointment as he did not relish Mr Kinnock's declared aim of
fighting a seat on Labour's national executive committee.
However, the reports of the discussions immediately provoked a hostile
reaction from Conservative backbenchers and opposition from the cabinet.
Several argued that Mr Kinnock was not appropriately qualified for the job
and should, anyway, be left in London in the hope that his presence would
undermine Mr Smith's new regime.
When the controversy over the Maastricht treaty deepened in the wake of the
Danish referendum result, Mr Kinnock's prospects faded. Last week, he
publicly claimed he had no interest in the Pounds 100,000-plus post -
signalling that the decision had gone against him.
The reappointment of Mr Millan alongside Sir Leon Brittan as British
commissioner leaves a solid, experienced administrator in place for the next
two years.
Mr Millan, who has been in charge of EC regional policy since 1989, served
in the Labour government as a junior minister in the 1960s and as secretary
of state for Scotland under Lord Callaghan.
Unlike some of his colleagues, Mr Millan has kept a low profile in Brussels.
He has earned a reputation for hard work and skilful bargaining in his
efforts to share out the Ecu60bn (at 1989 prices) allocated to poorer
regions between 1987 and 1992.
Mr Millan has indicated he would like to retain the regional policy
portfolio in the new Commission that is due to take office in January 1993.
He is understood to be pressing for a streamlining of responsibilities for
structural funds.
Observer, Page 19
</TEXT>
