<HEADLINE>
FT  21 OCT 92 / C&amp;G mortgage rate cut to 9.05%
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID BARCHARD
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
CHELTENHAM &amp; Gloucester, the seventh-largest building society, undercut the
rest of the market yesterday by moving its standard variable mortgage rate
down by 0.7 of a percentage point to 9.05 per cent from December 1.
Meanwhile, figures released yesterday suggest that societies had one of
their worst months for business ever in September - with activity on savings
and mortgage lending sharply down.
The new Cheltenham &amp; Gloucester rate compares with a standard mortgage
interest rate of about 9.25 per cent for other lenders. It will apply
immediately for new customers and from December 1 for existing borrowers.
Many new borrowers will also be given a discount of 1 percentage point,
bringing their mortgage interest rate down to 8.05 per cent.
Nationwide, the second-largest building society, and National Westminster
Bank have also cut mortgage interest rates. In both cases, the reduced
interest rates apply immediately for new customers and from December 1 for
existing ones.
From today, new borrowers with Nationwide will pay 9.29 per cent interest, a
reduction of 0.66 of a percentage point, although there will be slightly
larger cuts for customers with large loans.
NatWest has cut its mortgage loan rate by 0.74 of a percentage point to 9.25
per cent.
The business figures released yesterday by the Building Societies
Association show a net savings outflow of Pounds 264m in September, compared
with an inflow of Pounds 327m in August.
At the same time, mortgage lending dwindled to Pounds 446m, down from Pounds
1.7bn in each of the previous two months. The figure was the lowest monthly
total since 1982. One of the reasons for the sharp fall was the end of the
stamp-duty holiday in August.
New lending, agreed but not disbursed, dropped from Pounds 2.48bn in August
to Pounds 1.8bn. During the month, the housing market was extremely subdued,
with house prices falling by 3.1 per cent, according to the Halifax
house-price index.
Mr Mark Boleat, director-general of the association, said the market was
still beset with worries about unemployment and economic uncertainty, but
that the latest fall in base rates to 8 per cent might help revive consumer
sentiment.
</TEXT>
