<HEADLINE>
FT  21 OCT 92 / Loans fall signals deeper gloom
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER MARSH, Economics Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
FURTHER signs that the recession may be deepening came with news yesterday
that individuals and companies made a net repayment of loans to banks and
building societies last month, the first such event since records started 28
years ago.
The repayment, announced by the Bank of England yesterday, came to a
seasonally adjusted Pounds 700m. The news, together with weak figures for
growth of the money supply, adds to pressure for more cuts in interest rates
to expand the economy.
Other data from the Bank indicate that it, together with foreign central
banks, bought about Pounds 12.7bn in sterling on September 16 - Black
Wednesday - in a vain effort to lift the pound before the UK was forced to
leave the European exchange rate mechanism.
That number is consistent with market estimates that total intervention on
Black Wednesday was between Pounds 15bn and Pounds 20bn. Yesterday's numbers
do not include sterling purchases by the Bank using foreign currency
reserves lent to the UK authorities by foreign central banks which have not
yet been repaid.
In the year to September 30, M0, which mainly comprises cash and notes in
circulation, increased by 2.1 per cent compared with the previous 12 months.
The figure is roughly at the centre of the Treasury's target range of 0 per
cent to 4 per cent and underlines the lack of inflationary pressures.
Growth in M4, a broader measure of the money supply, which also takes in
bank and building society deposits, was similarly subdued. Between the same
two 12-month periods, M4 expanded by 5.1 per cent, after growth of a revised
5.5 per cent in the year to the end of August. In the 12 months to the end
of August, M0 expanded by a revised 2.4 per cent.
After changing its methods of making seasonal adjustments, the Bank altered
its previous assertion that individuals and companies made a repayment of
Pounds 500m to banks and building societies in March this year. It is now
recorded as a seasonally adjusted increase in loans of Pounds 974m.
The weak growth in the money supply last month may have been influenced by
the large intervention operations by the Bank of England and other European
central banks on Black Wednesday, draining cash from the UK banking system.
Backing up the indications of low economic demand, the British Bankers'
Association said the big commercial banks received repayments from companies
and consumers in September of nearly Pounds 1bn at an underlying level, the
first such repayment since March.
</TEXT>
