<HEADLINE>
FT  21 OCT 92 / The Coal Crisis: UDM leader to stand down
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID GOODHART, Labour Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR ROY LYNK, leader of the breakaway Union of Democratic Mineworkers, said
yesterday he felt so betrayed by the government's pit closure decision that
he would not stand for re-election.
Speaking from the bottom of the Silverhill mine in Nottinghamshire, where he
has spent the past five days and nights protesting at the closure decision,
Mr Lynk said he faced a credibility gap with his members and had decided 'to
jump before I am pushed'.
Members of the UDM, which represents about a third of British Coal's miners,
mainly in Nottinghamshire, worked through the 1984-85 pit strike and
subsequently enjoyed a close relationship with Conservative ministers. The
union remains opposed to privatisation but Mr Lynk has been a keen advocate
of taking an employee stake in the privatised pits.
Mr Lynk, who is 60 next month, said: 'I want to illustrate to the world the
obvious contempt the government and British Coal have got for moderate trade
union leaders.'
Mr Lynk was narrowly re-elected as president two years ago and in next
month's election would probably have lost to Mr Neil Greatrex, leader of the
union's Nottingham section. Mr Greatrex has always been more sceptical of
privatisation and more hostile to the government.
Mr Greatrex still faces Mr Arthur Morehouse, branch secretary at the
Thoresby pit, in the election for president. Even if Mr Greatrex wins, the
chances of swift rapprochement with the National Union of Mineworkers remain
slim.
Mr Greatrex said he hoped there would be a 'better rapport' with the NUM if
he was elected. He emphasised, though, that they would remain separate
organisations.
Mr Arthur Scargill, the NUM leader, will accept rapprochement only on his
terms: individual UDM members rejoining the NUM.
The TUC has enjoyed a strong revival in its credibility, not least among its
own member unions, during the pits crisis, according to senior officials.
An immediate consequence is likely to be a clear recommendation for a 'yes'
vote from the executive of the electricians' section of the AEEU craft union
in next year's ballot on whether the merged union should be in the TUC.
The electricians' union remains outside the TUC after disputes about
poaching of members, but after its merger with the AEU engineering union, a
TUC member, members of both unions are being balloted.
</TEXT>
