<HEADLINE>
FT  21 OCT 92 / World Trade News: UK machine-tool maker in Indian licensing
deal
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW BAXTER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BRIDGEPORT MACHINES, the Leicester-based machine tool builder, has signed an
important collaboration agreement under which Batliboi, the Indian
industrial conglomerate, will make Bridgeport horizontal machining centres
under licence.
The agreement stems from a Pounds 4m order won earlier this year by Batliboi
from the Ishapore-based Rifle Factory for 16 horizontal machining centres to
manufacture arms. Machining centres are automated, multi-function machine
tools.
Batliboi wanted access to the latest machine-tool technology so that it
could win the military order and subsequent commercial contracts. The deal
has taken four years to negotiate, and is the first such agreement in India
for Bridgeport. The UK company fought off competition from German rivals
that dominate the market for machine tools used in arms manufacture.
Mr Malcolm Taylor, Bridgeport's managing director, said collaboration was
'the key' to the Indian market, which has been very difficult for western
suppliers. 'But there is a general feeling that things are opening up
somewhat.'
Batliboi's Rifle Factory is worth about Pounds 1m in export business to
Bridgeport, which is supplying three complete machines and the key parts
such as spindle assemblies and Siemens controls for the other 13.
Once the contract is fulfilled, production will continue at Batliboi's
factory at Surat, Gujarat State.
</TEXT>
