<HEADLINE>
FT  21 OCT 92 / International Company News: Swedish property group in the
red
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT TAYLOR
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
NCC, one of Sweden's leading property and construction groups, made a loss
of SKr109m (Dollars 19m) for the first eight months of the year, compared
with a profit of SKr242m in the same period last year. These figures include
the group's share of profits from associated companies. Its consolidated
sales fell slightly to SKr14.3bn from SKr14.6bn.
Profits (after net financial items), which exclude the associated companies,
were down to SKr165m from SKr321m.
The company said it did not expect to make a profit for the whole of the
year. Mr Torsten Eriksson, NCC's president, said preliminary estimates
suggested a write-down requirement on its property portfolio of between
SKr700m and SKr1bn for the full year. He added that the company would have
negative, but improving, cash-flow through next year, with a positive one by
1994.
The company's real estate sector suffered a SKr187m loss, compared with one
of SKr70m for the same period of 1991, while it also made a SKr144 deficit
in its exchange-listed subsidiaries and associated companies.
The contraction in Sweden's construction sector continues to hit the group's
building activities, but NCC still made a SKr502m profit in that part of its
business compared with SKr506m for the same period of 1991.
The company also pointed out its on-going rationalisation programme as well
as an internal reorganisation had brought SKr500m in savings over the year
and it expected to reduce its balance sheet by SKr4bn this year compared
with 1991.
</TEXT>
