<HEADLINE>
FT  21 OCT 92 / International Company News: Colgate-Palmolive back in the
black in third term
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NIKKI TAIT
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
COLGATE-Palmolive, the US consumer products group, yesterday reported
after-tax profits of Dollars 128.8m for the three months to end-September,
on sales of Dollars 1.83bn.
The figure compares with a Dollars 197.4m loss in the same period of 1991,
but the previous year's results were depressed by a one-off restructuring
charge of Dollars 340m before tax.
Colgate said with this excluded net income would have shown a 34 per cent
increase year-on-year, and earnings per share a 15 per cent rise to 78
cents.
Mr Reuben Mark, Colgate's chairman, said all four geographical regions
showed higher sales and profits in the third quarter.
For the group overall, unit volume was up by 12 per cent, although the
advance partly reflected the purchase of the Mennen business in the US.
Without Mennen, there would have been a 5 per cent unit volume increase.
The third-quarter results bring Colgate's net profits for the first nine
months of 1992 to Dollars 367.1m, compared with Dollars 38m - after the
restructuring charge - in the same period of 1991.
</TEXT>
