<HEADLINE>
FT  21 OCT 92 / Overland relief convoys suspended by UN: Tudjman and Cosic
appeal for end to conflict in Bosnia
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By FRANCES WILLIAMS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   GENEVA
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE United Nations refugee agency said yesterday it had been forced to
suspend relief convoys along the only all-weather road into Bosnia because
uncontrolled 'warlords' were deliberately targeting aid trucks.
The suspension came as President Franjo Tudjman of Croatia and President
Dobrica Cosic of the rump Yugoslavia urged the warring parties in
Bosnia-Hercegovina to work for an end to the fighting and for an accord on a
new constitution for the republic.
The call was in a joint statement made last night at the international peace
talks in Geneva, under the chairmanship of Mr Cyrus Vance and Lord Owen. The
wording of the statement left little doubt the two presidents were agreed in
opposition to arguments by Bosnia's Moslem-led government that the republic
should not be divided along ethnic lines.
The presidents also agreed new steps towards normalising relations between
their two states following war in the second half of last year. Lord Owen
said the declaration was another 'building block' in the drive to construct
a peaceful edifice covering all the republics of former Yugoslavia.
A close aide to President Alija Izetbegovic of Bosnia, who was also at the
Geneva talks, discounted a claim on Croatian radio that the Bosnian leader
had been toppled during his absence by a pro-Serb faction. 'We hear a lot of
these claims,' the aide said. 'Most of them are spread by people who have
their own reasons to make trouble.' He said the president was heading back
to Sarajevo today.
The suspension of relief convoys leaves the Sarajevo airlift as the only
means of transporting humanitarian supplies to the Bosnian capital and
central Bosnia-Hercegovina, where more than 750,000 people face starvation
and freezing temperatures this winter.
Mrs Sadako Ogata, UN High Commissioner for Refugees, said the shelling of
two convoys on the Mostar-Sarajevo road last Friday was yet another example
of the failure of the parties to the conflict to live up to their
commitments.
UNHCR officials estimate they need to provide 9,230 tonnes of food and other
supplies to 1.6m Bosnians each week in winter. Last week it delivered just
1,130 tonnes.
Mr Cedric Thornberry, director of civil affairs with the UN protection force
(Unprofor) in ex-Yugoslavia, said in Geneva yesterday the situation in
Bosnia was 'becoming quite desperate, with hundreds of thousands of people
displaced from their homes, many of them wandering the roads and trying to
survive in the hills'.
General Satish Nambiar, the Unprofor commander, said the extra 6,000 or so
UN troops promised to escort aid convoys and open roads would be deployed by
mid-November.
Gen Nambiar also said Unprofor would protest to the Bosnian Serb leadership
over an incident yesterday when its commander in Sarajevo and three aides
were held briefly at gunpoint at a checkpoint.
Gen Nambiar confirmed that the withdrawal of Yugoslav forces from the
Prevlaca peninsula in Croatia had been completed.
Blind eye, Page 19
