<HEADLINE>
FT  21 OCT 92 / Major shifts economic policy
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP STEPHENS, Political Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR JOHN MAJOR last night unveiled a significant shift in economic policy to
give priority to growth and employment as his government sought to restore
its battered authority at Westminster.
After Mr Michael Heseltine, the trade and industry secretary, agreed to
widen the scope of his promised review of closures in the coal industry, the
prime minister signalled that he hoped for further cuts in British interest
rates.
With Conservative MPs deeply gloomy about the economic outlook and the
Treasury forecasting no early end to the recession, Mr Major said the
government intended to build a strategy for growth and jobs. In an interview
with ITN after the new approach was unveiled by Downing Street, Mr Major
said: 'A strategy for growth is what we need; a strategy for growth is what
we are going to have.'
Earlier he indicated that international deflationary pressures should allow
borrowing costs to drop below the present 8 per cent level without risking
an upsurge in inflation. The government would not be indifferent to the
level of the pound on the foreign exchange markets but it had no specific
target.
Mr Major told colleagues that he wanted an 'early, strong but sustainable'
recovery which would take advantage of the competitive edge provided by
sterling's devaluation, while keeping inflation low.
But he also warned colleagues that next month's Autumn Statement would
foreshadow the tightest squeeze on public sector pay in recent memory to
convince financial markets that the government remained serious about
containing the pace of price rises.
The prime minister said he was determined that the sharp cuts in most
Whitehall spending programmes needed to meet the Treasury's overall spending
targets should not fall on projects which had a direct impact on 'jobs and
growth'. That implies that increases in public sector pay will be held below
2 per cent and might be frozen.
He indicated that he wanted the government to offset the inevitable
reductions in some capital spending programmes by scrapping Whitehall rules
inhibiting private sector involvement in large infrastructure projects.
One suggestion last night was that reductions, for example, in the
Department of Transport's road-building programme could be matched by a
drive to make it much easier to allow the private sector to build toll
roads.
Mr Major's stance - signalled by Downing Street and later confirmed in a
series of television interviews - marks the beginning of a determined
attempt to restore his grip on the Tory party at Westminster.
Senior ministers conceded that sterling's ignominious exit from the European
exchange rate mechanism last month and this week's U-turn over coal had
severely weakened the government's - and the prime minister's  - authority.
Mr Major had now responded to the unease among Conservative MPs and in the
country at large by signalling that his first priority was an end to the
recession.
He also made it clear that on one issue - his absolute determination to
ratify the Maastricht treaty - he was not prepared to give any ground to his
critics on the Conservative backbenches.
The Maastricht bill is scheduled to return to the House of Commons next
month and Mr Major told colleagues: 'I think people would be well-advised to
accept that I say what I mean on the subject of European policy. If people
don't trust me, they had better find someone they do trust.'
Mr Major's new emphasis on economic growth rather than the defeat of
inflation was seen at Westminster as evidence that the threatened rebellion
by Conservative MPs over the government's original coal closure plan
reflected much deeper unease over the depths of the recession.
With the public spending cuts under consideration in the run-up to the
Autumn Statement threatening much larger job losses in both the public and
private sectors, Mr Major was concerned to stress that his commitment was to
economic recovery.
But his decision to emphasise that priority appeared also to mark a more
fundamental re-assessment by the Treasury of the balance of risks in
policy-making after the latest batch of gloomy economic news.
Despite the sharp devaluation of the pound since last month and the
accompanying two-point reduction in interest rates, the government now
appears convinced that further deflation poses a greater risk than an
upsurge in inflation.
