<HEADLINE>
FT  21 OCT 92 / Heseltine broadens energy review: Major tries to restore
authority by rebalancing economic policy towards recovery
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PHILIP STEPHENS, Political Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE GOVERNMENT was confi-dent last night that it had headed off a House of
Commons defeat over coal closures by broadening the scope of its planned
review to include a detailed analysis of Britain's long-term energy
requirements.
The latest concessions to Conservative critics came as Mr John Major
signalled a drive to restore his battered authority at Westminster by
rebalancing his economic policy to emphasise the priority of recovery.
The prime minister told colleagues he was willing to respond to the depth of
the recession with further cuts in interest rates if public spending was
kept under control. But he made clear that on one issue - his determination
to ratify the Maastricht treaty - he was not prepared to give any ground to
his critics on the Conservative backbenches.
With Conservative MPs deeply gloomy about the economic outlook, Mr Major
indicated that international deflationary pressures might allow interest
rates to drop below the 8 per cent mark without risking an upsurge in
inflation.
But he also warned that next month's autumn economic statement must see the
tightest squeeze on public sector pay in recent memory if the Treasury was
to convince financial markets that it remained serious about containing the
pace of price rises.
The prime minister is said to be determined that the sharp cuts in most
Whitehall spending programmes needed to meet the Treasury's targets should
not fall on projects which have a direct impact on 'jobs and growth'. That
implies that increases in public sector pay will be below 2 per cent and
might be frozen.
He has also indicated that he wants the government to offset the inevitable
reductions in some capital spending programmes by scrapping Whitehall rules
which inhibit private sector involvement in large-scale infrastructure
projects. One suggestion last night was that reductions in the Department of
Transport's road-building programme could be matched by a drive to make it
much easier to allow the private sector to build toll roads.
Mr Major's decision to rebalance his economic policy came as senior
ministers engaged in a frantic effort to restore discipline among Tory MPs
after the government's embarrassing U-turn over the bulk of its coal closure
programme. The latest concessions on the pit review were foreshadowed by Mr
Michael Heseltine, trade and industry secretary, in meetings with Tory MPs
designed to ensure their support in today's Labour-sponsored debate on the
industry.
Mr Heseltine promised that the planned review of the future of 21 threatened
pits would be wide-ranging and open, embracing an strategic analysis of
Britain's energy requirements.
That pledge was reinforced by Lord Wakeham, Lord Privy Seal, who told the
House of Lords that a whole range of issues would be covered by the review -
including the level of coal imports, the relationship between electricity
suppliers and the owners of gas generation stations and allegations that
some suppliers were abusing their market positions.
Mr Heseltine had suggested previously that the review would be much more
narrowly focused on the viability of the threatened pits, but was forced to
give further ground to quell the disquiet among Conservative MPs.
After the latest concessions he received a public assurance that the
executive committee of the powerful backbench 1922 committee would now urge
all Tory MPs to back the government - and a tacit acknowledgement that his
own cabinet position was now secure.
Mr Major emphasised the government's willingness to listen to its critics
during clashes in the House of Commons with Mr John Smith, the Labour
leader.
He stressed that all the evidence given to the review would be available
publicly and that the government would co-operate fully with a planned
inquiry of the trade and industry select committee into the pit closures.
The judgment of Conservative party managers at Westminster last night was
that the concessions would ensure that all but a handful of potential rebels
on its own side would now support the government against the Labour motion
demanding a complete moratorium on all closures.
