<DOCNO>FT924-12523</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CJTB8AGUFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>921020
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  20 OCT 92 / Chase recovery continues with 29% rise in profits
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALAN FRIEDMAN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
A 29 per cent rise in Chase Manhattan's third-quarter net profits showed
that the recovery is continuing at the big New York bank that has spent the
past two years slashing costs and changing its strategy.
Chase, which has reduced its workforce by 8,000 people and reorganised
itself to concentrate on retail banking in the New York area and wholesale
banking globally, turned in Dollars 176m (Pounds 102.3m) of third-quarter
net income. This translates into earnings per share of 94 cents, compared
with 79 cents a year ago.
Although the Chase results were helped by an increase in net interest
revenues - from Dollars 863m a year ago to Dollars 898m in the third quarter
just ended - the bank is still coping with higher bad debt provisions,
especially related to its loan exposure in the depressed US commercial
property market.
The third-quarter provision for possible loan losses was Dollars 320m,
compared with Dollars 265m a year ago. The bank said it expected such
provisions to continue at relatively high levels.
Net loan write-offs totalled Dollars 321m, almost half the Dollars 656m
level of a year ago.
At the end of September Chase had Dollars 7.4bn of domestic commercial
property loans on its books, down from Dollars 8.9bn a year ago. Some
Dollars 2.23bn of these loans were classified as non-performing, down
slightly from Dollars 2.36bn a year before.
For the first nine months of 1992 Chase achieved Dollars 470m of net
profits, up from Dollars 385m in the same period last year. Bad debt
provisions were Dollars 915m, up from Dollars 770m in the same period of
1991.
However, net loan write-offs in the first nine months of 1992 fell to
Dollars 912m from Dollars 1.6bn in the first three quarters of last year.
Mr Tom Labrecque, chairman, said the third-quarter results reflected the
bank's programme of building its core businesses.
He said Chase had further strengthened its capital base, reaching a Tier One
ratio (capital as a percentage of net risk-weighted assets) of 6.5 per cent,
up from 5.2 per cent a year ago.
Chase's return on assets rose to 0.71 per cent from 0.53 per cent in
September 1991. The bank's return on equity was 12 per cent, up from 10.5
per cent a year ago.
Wall Street reacted favourably to the Chase earnings figures, marking the
bank's share price Dollars  7/8 higher to Dollars 23 3/8.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
