<HEADLINE>
FT  20 OCT 92 / International Company News: Reebok results fall below Wall
Street expectations
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KAREN ZAGOR
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
REEBOK International, the US sports shoe maker, yesterday posted
disappointing earnings for the third quarter and warned that its
fourth-quarter results would trail earlier projections.
Net income for the quarter advanced to Dollars 74.4m, or 80 cents a share,
on sales of Dollars 863.2m, from Dollars 66.2m, or 71 cents, on sales of
Dollars 764.3m a year earlier.
Most analysts had expected earnings of about 83 cents a share in the latest
quarter.
The results were released after Wall Street's close, but shares in Reebok
were unavailable for late trading yesterday. The stock closed at Dollars 29,
up Dollars  5/8 on the day.
Mr Paul Fireman, chairman and chief executive, said the company had cut its
expected full-year earnings from operations to a range of Dollars 2.50 to
Dollars 2.55 a share from earlier estimates of Dollars 2.70 to Dollars 2.85.
Although sales of Reebok and Rockport brands increased in the quarter, sales
of Ellesse and AVIA fell sharply. Ellesse sales dropped to Dollars 12.2m
from Dollars 20.4m, while AVIA lost 22.4 per cent to Dollars 36.4m.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 32
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT924-12533</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CJTB8AGKFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>921020
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  20 OCT 92 / International Company News: American Cyanamid shows
improvement
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KAREN ZAGOR
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
AMERICAN Cyanamid, the US pharmaceuticals and chemicals company, yesterday
posted third-quarter net earnings of Dollars 61m, or 68 cents a share,
compared with Dollars 56m, or 60 cents, a year earlier.
Earnings per share advanced more sharply than net earnings, thanks to fewer
shares outstanding in the 1992 quarter.
Sales rose 7 per cent to Dollars 1.2bn from Dollars 1.12bn.
The company's medical group saw higher sales and earnings in the quarter,
led by pharmaceuticals and medical devices.
Agricultural sales also advanced in the three months, and the group narrowed
its traditional third-quarter loss.
Cyanamid, which has been moving away from the chemicals business, said
chemical sales fell in the quarter, largely reflecting the divestment of
several businesses and the discontinuation of some product lines.
Operating earnings for the chemicals group, however, rose in the quarter,
led by paper chemicals, resin products and water treatment chemicals.
