<HEADLINE>
FT  20 OCT 92 / Lloyds plans to shut down merchant banking division
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID BARCHARD
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
LLOYDS BANK, the smallest of the Big Four clearers by asset size, is to
close Lloyds Merchant Bank, its loss-making merchant-banking operation, and
transfer three other business units to the parent bank.
The decision to shut Lloyds Merchant Bank, a tiny operation compared with
the merchant bank arm of Barclays or National Westminster, comes after
several years in which it has incurred losses.
In the first half of this year Lloyds Merchant Bank announced a loss of
Pounds 14m. The bank will be gradually phased out of existence during the
next two years, but only 50 jobs will be lost from its 360 workforce.
At the same time, Lloyds is to transfer Lloyds Investment Managers, Lloyds
Development Capital, its venture capital arm, and Lloyds Bank Stockbrokers
to report directly to the parent bank.
When the bank reported an 11 per cent increase in interim pre-tax group
profits to Pounds 369m in August, investment managing and stockbroking were
reported to be doing well.
The closure of Lloyds Merchant Bank is the latest in a series of withdrawals
by Lloyds from unprofitable activities in the UK and overseas to concentrate
on more profitable retail banking lines of business and small and
medium-sized corporate business.
At the time of Big Bang in 1986, Lloyds Merchant Bank was intended to
compete with the merchant banking arms of Lloyds' main rivals, but its range
of activities contracted steadily in the late 1980s.
</TEXT>
