FT  20 OCT 92 / Bush fights to regain initiative in final TV debate
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GEORGE GRAHAM
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
PRESIDENT George Bush last night launched his most confident and pointed
attack so far on Governor Bill Clinton, in a late attempt to revitalise his
flagging campaign for re-election on November 3 and to dent his Democratic
opponent's big lead.
After hesitant performances in the first two televised debates between the
candidates, Mr Bush took the offensive in last night's third debate to
accuse Mr Clinton of trying systematically to take both sides on every
issue.
'There's a pattern here of appealing to the auto workers and then trying to
appeal to the spotted owl crowd. You can't do that as president,' Mr Bush
said.
Few analysts last night believed that a strong debate performance would be
enough to do more than nibble at Mr Clinton's lead in the polls, which in
the past 24 hours have shown him ahead by between 12 and 18 percentage
points.
Yet the president at least dispelled the pervasive reports of recent days
suggesting that he had already given up the fight.
He met the expectations of his supporters by delivering an attack on his
opponent's record as governor of Arkansas and by drawing a philosophical
distinction between himself and Mr Clinton, who he said was 'still talking
about spending more and taxing more'.
In a stinging barb, Mr Bush warned Americans to 'watch your wallet' if Mr
Clinton wins.
Mr Bush got support from an unexpected quarter when Mr Ross Perot, the
independent candidate in the presidential election, dismissed as irrelevant
Mr Clinton's experience as governor of such a small state as Arkansas. 'I
could say I ran a small grocery store on the corner and extrapolate that and
say I could run Walmart; that's just not so,' he quipped.
But Mr Perot reserved his harshest words for Mr Bush, whom he accused of
building up foreign dictators and then seeking to exonerate himself by
admitting error.
'Create Saddam Hussein with taxpayers' money, step up to the plate and say
it was a mistake. Create Manuel Noriega, step up to the plate and say it was
a mistake . . . that's leadership, folks,' he jeered.
While Mr Clinton appeared at times defensive, many analysts felt immediately
after the debate that he had done at least enough to cement his already
solid lead in a majority of states.
With last night's final debate out of the way, President Bush is heading
south to bolster his flagging support in the two Carolinas, Georgia and
possibly Florida. Governor Clinton is embarking on a 'winning the west'
tour, including stops in Nevada, Wyoming and Montana.
Ghost of campaign past drives Democrats, Page 5
