markets, as well as the rise of the guilder against the dollar. In the first
half, Oce had reported an 8 per cent rise in net profit.
News of the decline caused Oce's shares to fall sharply on the Amsterdam
Stock Exchange, where they closed down 19 per cent at Fl 38.50 from Fl 47.50
on Friday. Oce is the first large Dutch company to release its third-quarter
figures, with most others due to report in late October and early November.
The figures mean Oce's net profit in the first nine months was virtually
flat at Fl 70.0m.
