<HEADLINE>
FT  20 OCT 92 / International Company News: Production gains lift American
Barrick
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NIKKI TAIT
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
AMERICAN Barrick, the Canadian gold producer which last year had abortive
merger talks with Newmont Mining, yesterday reported after-tax profits of
Dollars 49.5m in the three months to end-September. This compared with
Dollars 28.2m in the same period a year earlier.
Revenues were up from Dollars 92.4m to Dollars 143.5m, while earnings per
share increased from 20 cents to 35 cents.
American Barrick has now reported after-tax profits of Dollars 109.4m in the
first nine months of 1992, against Dollars 68.4m in the same period of 1991.
The company said gold production totalled 838,711 ounces in the nine-month
period of 1992. This represents a substantial increase on the 595,524 ounces
seen in the same months of 1991, and was attributed to a 66 per cent
increase in production at the Goldstrike Mine in Nevada.
American Barrick also said it had realised an average price of Dollars 426
an ounce for its gold sales this year, compared with the Comex average gold
price of Dollars 346 - reflecting the company's hedging programme.
It predicted that it should meet its 1992 production target of 1.2m ounces,
with fourth-quarter results improving further.
The shares rose Dollars 5/8 to Dollars 30 5/8.
</TEXT>
